Although I wasn’t adopted, many of Cyril the squirrel’s lifelong struggles around this theme somewhat mirror my own. Adoption *does* play a part in my life. My own astonishment and dismay at the hypocrisy so prevalent among the leadership of organized religion is present in this novel. I miss my mother. review: Not a child abuse story. Not a romance, at least not in the traditional sense. This is a story about two characters’ slow recalibration of normal so tNot a child abuse story. Not a romance, at least not in the traditional sense. This is a story about two characters’ slow recalibration of normal so that their lives can begin to make sense. All made much more difficult in an era when prejudice and sexism are worn on the sleeve and not shamefully so. Is this a good and well-written book? Yes it is, but I felt kept at arm’s length. This is often the case when the main character isn’t likable in the usual sense. It’s a challenge getting to know her, and the tone of her matter of fact observations, fraught with meaning as they often were, kept me at a distance, looking down at characters I had trouble peering within or for whom I had difficulty feeling any profound emotional affect....more

review: Much more than a novel about civilization teetering toward oblivion, Ma creates a unique, nuanced, conflicted protagonist who comes to the events at tMuch more than a novel about civilization teetering toward oblivion, Ma creates a unique, nuanced, conflicted protagonist who comes to the events at the end of the novel most begrudgingly. Utterly beautiful writing. Perfectly placed sentences. I’ve rarely felt so enthralled or unnerved, both often in the same breath. Severance straddles the line between horror and satire credibly, and Ma creates a sense of realism amidst extremely evocative circumstances without any sense of overreach. review: Lovely fable that is, ultimately, the work of a man who continues to look his impending mortality head-on and finds peace where the finish line might Lovely fable that is, ultimately, the work of a man who continues to look his impending mortality head-on and finds peace where the finish line might be. This is an elegant story written with a subtlety and nuance for which King is commonly underrated, and when employed by the writer, often misunderstood as weak. For a writer of his age, King’s audience skews young, and the appeal of a story like this might not be understood. That’s ok. It’s just not a story for them, for right now. The monster here is that there is no monster. Just a look into one man’s travels from here to there. Recommended....more
